Research Question:
How do the topological properties of natural language dependency structures—specifically
arity, tree depth, and graph density differ from those of size-matched, randomly generated
directed acyclic graphs (DAGs)?
Motivation:
Despite the fact that there have been many studies undertaken in the area of language
since ancient times, there is still an apparently simple question that remains unresolved: Is
there a necessity for the language to be what it is, or is it just mere coincidence? There are
many related questions to this, among which are brain data processing, human language
formation, and computer interpretation of language.
• Constraints on Cognition: Grammar is not arbitrary; it is a result of the constraints of
human working memory.
• Real-Time Comprehension: Humans need simple grammatical structures for word-by-
word comprehension of speech to prevent "memory crashes."
• Linguistic Universals: When different languages like Hindi and Japanese have identical
graph properties, it shows that these constraints are biological rather than cultural.
• AI & NLP: Knowing these constraints enables us to create better parsing algorithms and
human-like AI systems.
• Research Gaps: Existing research only considers word distance, whereas this project
includes a comprehensive topological approach against random chance.
BackGround Context:
Language as a Graph
Language among human beings is not made up of a linear string of words; rather, it is a
structured network of relationships. Dependency grammar presents language such that in
a particular sentence, the nodes of a directed graph correspond to words, while edges
represent grammatical relations between the nodes. These dependency graphs are, in
general, directed acyclic graphs (DAGs).
The Cognitive Hypothesis
The central question raised by cognitive linguistics lies in whether the organisation of
language is completely arbitrary and purely historical, or is it somehow connected to the
structure of the human mind? George Miller's groundbreaking paper written back in 1956
showed that a human short-term memory could remember approximately 7 ± 2 chunks of
information. Further experiments conducted by Cowan in 2001 revealed, however, that
such a figure was rather too high, and suggested only 4 ± 1 chunks of information in case
if the listener had to keep the sentence syntactically open. In case if a listener was forced
Dependency Length Minimization (DLM)
According to hypothesis, grammar systems across languages have word-order constraints
such that the sum of linear distances between heads and dependents is minimised. The
validity of DLM has been established through empirical testing in numerous languages.
This research, on the other hand, raises a different kind of inquiry regarding the structure
of dependency relationships, more specifically, their arity, depth, and density.
