Analysis of dependency structure as DAGs is necessary due to the conflict that lies at the
heart of linguistic complexity against human mental capacity.
Four key areas make up the importance of the project in question:
• Isolating Biological Rules: By testing humans against random “noise,” you will
determine the grammatical rules that are essential to biology (biological necessity of
brain processes) or merely happen by chance due to math.
• Cognitive Milestones: The fact that our languages have lower levels of depth and
arities indicates that there are milestones set by human brains with respect to
memory and language.
• Universality: The same structures found in different languages, including Hindi,
Arabic, and Japanese, indicate that cognitive limitations apply universally to all
humans.
• Optimization of AI: This will be helpful in determining whether artificial intelligence,
like LLMs, “thinks” like a human or creates non-biological structures.
Hypotheses and predictions:
The hypotheses of the present study are logically implied by the cognitive constraints
theory presented in the problem statement of the research. The natural language
dependency structures which have been formed on the basis of human working memory
capacity and real-time parsing requirements should have topological characteristics that
significantly differ from those of random DAGs of comparable complexity. Each of the three
topological characteristics – arity, tree depth, and graph density – forms an individual
hypothesis.
Hypothesis 1: Arity is Bounded in Natural Language
Formal Statement:
H0(1):Fnl(a)=Frand(a)
H1(1) :a¯(nl) <a¯(rand)
where Fnl(a) and Frand(a) represent the respective empirical distribution functions for
mean node arity for natural language and random directed acyclic graphs, while a¯ is the
mean node arity averaged across all non-leaf nodes of a graph.
Reasoning:
In a DAG created randomly with n nodes, the placement of the edges is arbitrary, and a
node may theoretically have many dependents. Based on Cowan’s (2001) finding that
there are 4 ± 1 active chunks in working memory, one would expect the average arity of
natural language dependency graphs to be small and constrained, falling between 1 and 3
dependents per head, while random DAGs of equal size would yield a larger and greater
arity.
Prediction:
2
The empirical CDF for arity in natural language DAGs is expected to be highly shifted to
the left of that of random DAGs. The D-statistic in the two-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov
test would be above the critical value when α=0.05, thus rejecting H0(1).We can anticipate
a¯NL ∈[1,3] and a¯rand ≫3
This bound is predicted to be consistent across all languages in the sample — English,
Japanese, Turkish and Arabic despite their differing morphological and word-order
typologies.
Hypothesis 2: Tree Depth is Shallower in Natural Language
Formal Statement:
H0(2) :Gnl (d)=Grand (d)
H1(2) :d¯nl <d¯rand
where Gnl(d) and Grand(d) represent the empirical cumulative distribution functions
(CDFs) for maximum path depths, while d is the mean depth of trees within the corpus,
computed as:
d(G)=max dist(root, v) ,v∈V
where dist(root, v) is the distance from the root node to the node v.
Reasoning:
Tree depth reflects how much centre embedding or recursion there is within a
sentence.The capacity of human memory runs out after two to three nested levels, making
it impossible to understand sentences that are too complex. Therefore, natural language
avoids having deep tree structures, irrespective of the length of sentences, while random
DAGs develop further without such biological limitations.
Prediction:
The depth distribution of natural language DAGs will be significantly shallower and less
variable than that of random DAGs. We predict:
d¯NL ≪d¯rand
The specific prediction is that natural language tree depth will scale sub-linearly with
sentence length n, possibly even logarithmically, as O(log n), while the depth of random
DAGs would scale more sharply. The K-S test will reject H0(2) at α=0.05.
Hypothesis 3: Graph Density is Lower in Natural Language
Formal Statement:
H0(3) :PNL (ρ)=Prand (ρ)
H1(3) :ρ¯ NL <ρ¯ rand
where graph density ρ is defined as:
ρ(G)=|E|/n(n−1)
with ∣E∣ the number of directed edges and n the number of nodes. For a dependency
tree,∣E∣=n−1 by definition, giving:
ρtree (G)=n(n−1)/n−1 =1/n.
Reasoning:
Trees in natural languages exhibit mathematical sparsity, with the edges restricted to n-1.
Although random directed acyclic graphs may tend towards greater density, density in
human languages tends to be less than 1/n due to their tree nature. Empirical experiments
would show the effects of multi-headed structures on this inefficiency gap.
Prediction:
3
The density profile of NLDAGs is expected to be considerably lower and more compact
compared to that of the random DAGs and exhibit a clearly declining trend with sentence
length n. The K-S test will reject the null hypothesis H0(3) for α=0.05.
