All three hypotheses will be tested using the two-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test at
significance level α=0.05, applied separately per language and then pooled across
languages to assess universality.
Methods (including brief description of data used):
Pipeline consists of four stages:
Data Acquisition→Graph Construction→Baseline Generation→Statistical
Comparison.
Stage 1: Data acquisition
• Source: Uses project Universal Dependencies that provides structured data in the form
of sentences in over 100 different languages.
• Languages: English, Japanese, Turkish, and Arabic (selected languages because of
different grammatical rules).
• Sample size: At least 5,000 sentences per language; all sentences have length of 3 to
50 words to ensure statistical validity.
Stage 2: Metrics calculation
Sentences are modeled as Directed Acyclic Graphs (DAG). Three major metrics should be
calculated:
• Arity: Average number of children for each word in the DAG.
• Tree Depth: Maximum path from the root word in DAG to leaf node; reflects degree of
nesting in sentence structure.
• Graph Density: Number of edges relative to number of potential edges in graph;
measures complexity in sentence structure.
Stage 3: Random Baseline generation
In order to assess uniqueness of human language, randomly created sentences are used
for comparison purposes.
• Prüfer sequence algorithm: Provides possibility of creating random trees based on
sentences.
• Size matching: Random trees generated per sentence are of equal size as real-world
trees.
• Neutrality: This technique is considered impartial as the computer will not prefer any
specific configuration, hence creating a completely chaotic baseline.
4
Stage 4: Statistical Analysis
• Kolmogorov-Smirnov (K-S) Test: A statistical method that determines whether
there is any significant difference between the distributions of the "Human" and
"Random" categories. This method is superior to a normal t-test since it analyses
the entire distribution rather than just the mean value.
Result:
These findings prove that natural language is considerably more efficient and orderly than
mere randomness. In all four languages examined (English, Japanese, Turkish, and
Arabic), the research revealed an innate "Human Signature" within the linguistic structure:
• Arity (Branching): Natural language demonstrates high average arities (≈1.68 - 1.92)
compared to the disorderly random graphs that show twice as much branching (≈3.28 -
3.52). It implies a strict biological limit on how many connections our brain can store
simultaneously.
• Depth (Nesting): Sentences formulated by humans are shallower than those generated
randomly. As opposed to the growing depth of random structures, the human-generated
ones expand horizontally to keep the hierarchical organisation simple enough.
• Density (Connectivity): The language is sparse; words only refer to nearby nodes. In
contrast, the average density of the random graph is about 2.5 times higher.
Main Findings:
The Kolmogorov-Smirnov tests were significant (p < 0.001) for all languages tested.
The identical nature of these patterns in such different language groups indicates that
grammar is a biological, rather than cultural, adaptation.
Theoretical implications (theoretical implications of the results):
The findings of the current research demonstrate three empirical properties about natural
language dependency DAGs: their smaller arity, shorter depth, and lesser graph density
when compared to randomly generated DAGs of equal size across four distinct typological
families.
1.Grammar as a Cognitive Artifact
This study supports the hypothesis that grammar follows constraints imposed by the
mind’s processing capabilities, not arbitrary linguistic rules.
• Arity Bound (a ~ 2):Consistent with limitations of working memory capacity (4±1
chunks), this allows for heads not to overload cognitive processes during parsing.
• Depth Bound O(log n): As sentences become longer, they become more expansive but
less deep to prevent “memory crashes” due to excessive recursion.
• Sparse Structure: Lower density makes it possible to keep connections related to each
individual word close to that word, not spread throughout the system.This reinforces the
theory that language has been highly optimized, balancing expressiveness and biology.
2.Implications for Dependency Length Minimization
The current study extends DLM through mathematical proof that cognitive optimization
takes place on two different levels:
• Structure level: The “map” (structure) of the sentence is predetermined based on
its arity and depth, to prevent the person from getting overwhelmed.
• Order level: The words are arranged in a linear form such that related concepts
stay close together.
5
Language is not optimized only for its linear progression of sound, rather, it must first be
optimized in a hierarchically efficient manner before the first word has been uttered. The
theory that grammar may be a graph-theoretic solution to biological constraints becomes
ever more convincing.
3. Language Evolution and Biological Universals
The universal pattern found above implies that grammatical structures are not determined
by cultural and genealogical factors, but by biological constraints. In the same way that we
cannot produce certain vocal sounds because of the structure of our vocal apparatus, so
It’s not possible to create sentences with arbitrary structures because of the limited
cognitive abilities of humans.
4.Implications for Language Acquisition
There are biological restrictions on how complicated sentence structures can be, then this
should manifest itself during language acquisition. This summary explains their findings:
• Developmental Growth Trajectory: Along with maturing working memory,
children's sentences should increase in complexity, in terms of both arity and depth.
• The Adult Asymptote: In addition to increasing in complexity, sentences that
children learn to make should eventually reach an asymptote within the parameters
found in the study, which correspond to about (a ~ 2, d ~ 4-5).
• Proof by Cognitive: One can prove through the study of databases of children like
CHILDES that there is actually any development in terms of complexity in the
utterances of children, and once it achieves its peak possible level, it becomes
certain that these constraints are biological rather than learned.
5. Implications for Computational Linguistics and NLP
There are some important implications of this paper for Computational Linguistics and
Natural Language Processing :
• Parser Optimization through Pruning: It's safe to ignore excessively complex and
deep syntactic structures beyond those allowed for humans.
• Attention Efficiently: As language is sparse in nature, costly O(n^2) attention
mechanism becomes inefficient as well. The mechanism of sparse attention not
only saves time but also linguistically correct.
• Error Identification: Deeper and high arities structures could be helpful in catching
errors while parsing or for detecting adversarial inputs.
• Efficiency of Sampling: Training of models on pre-expectation of shallowness and
sparsity makes learning more efficient for resource-poor languages.
